"hardware irq 0", either it can be special (eg some <br />system-only irq not used by any drivers) or the irq numbers can/must be <br />remapped.<br /><br />ARM already converted to the generic irq layer, and there are actually <br />parts of that that know that irq 0 has special meaning. Like the <br />autoprobing and spurious irq handling. Of course, ARM may not care, and <br />the generic code is generally trying to avoid any assumptions, but it's <br />still true that all generic _drivers_ do the whole "if (irq)" thing.<br /><br />Yeah, yeah, we've let NO_IRQ poison some subsystems (like IDE and <br />apparently parts of i2c), but that was a mistake.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
